		<section id="denim-dilemmas" class="two-col">
			<h2>Denim <span class="desktop"><hr/></span> Dilemmas</h2>
			<p class="">Our resident denim expert, Wanda Rivets (wink, wink),<br> has a solution to every style quandary.</p>
			<div class="col">
				<div class="image">
					<img src="/b/fashion/images/projects/denim/denim-styles/editorial-4.jpg" alt=""/>
					<a class="normal-brand-footer brand-footer" id="j-brand-light-wash" href="/shop/product/?ID=2814054">J Brand</a>
					<a class="normal-brand-footer brand-footer second-brand" id="levis-light-wash" href="/shop/product/?ID=2814062">Levi's</a>
				</div>
				<p><strong>Q.</strong> Dear Wanda Rivets: I don’t know what’s happening, but I suddenly find myself drawn to super-bleached washes and maybe even acid-washed styles. Should I get my eyes checked?
				<br> <strong>—Blurry in Boca</strong></p>
				<p><strong>A.</strong> Dear Blurry: Fret not! This jean-demic is sweeping the nation and it couldn’t be more on trend. Blotchy, barely blue and subtle acid washes marched down the spring runways on jackets and jeans to give these bleach-splattered styles a total model-off-duty rather than mom-needs-a-closet-update twist.</p>
				<p><a href="/shop/womens-apparel/jeans/Wash/Light%20Blue?id=5545" id="levis-light-jeans" class="link">LIGHT-WASH JEANS</a></p>
				<p><a href="/shop/womens-apparel/denim-jackets-denim-bombers?id=1005880" id="denim-jackets" class="link">DENIM JACKETS</a></p>
			</div>
			<div class="col">
				<div class="image">
					<img src="/b/fashion/images/projects/denim/denim-styles/editorial-5.jpg" alt=""/>
					<a class="normal-brand-footer brand-footer" id="ag-high-impact-hues" href="/shop/product/?ID=2814953">AG</a>
					<a class="normal-brand-footer brand-footer second-brand" id="j-brand-high-impact-hues" href="/shop/product/?ID=2810565">J Brand</a>
				</div>
				<p><strong>Q.</strong> Dear Wanda Rivets: I love the look of ultra-saturated colored denim--but not the way my cobalt jeans leave my hands looking blue and half-frozen by the end of the day. How can I make sure that same dye doesn’t get all over the rest of my laundry? <br><strong>—My Hamper Is Full in Huntsville</strong></p>
				<p><strong>A.</strong> Dear Hamper: Fire up the washer, because we’ve got an easy way to keep colorful pairs looking pristine. First, you have to sort (we’re particularly looking at you, Big Red, the culprit of my white-tee-is-now-salmon mishap). Colorfast brights (think hot pinks, purples, oranges and reds) can go together, washed in cool water to keep fading to a minimum. To test if an item will bleed, spray a section of your new jeans with water or swish them in a sink to see if any dye is released. If so, that pair should be washed solo for now.</p>
				<a href="/shop/womens-apparel/jeans/Jean_trends/High-Impact%20Hues?id=5545" id="shop-hight-impact-hues"  class="link">SHOP HIGH-IMPACT HUES</a>
			</div>
		</section>

